# ============================================================
# .gitignore — tells Git which files/folders to NEVER track
# ============================================================
# WHY THIS MATTERS: without this file, you risk accidentally
# committing huge cache folders, OS junk files, or sensitive
# local config — bloating your repo and possibly leaking data.

# Python cache & bytecode
__pycache__/
*.pyc
*.pyo

# Jupyter checkpoint files (auto-saved by Jupyter, not needed in git)
.ipynb_checkpoints/

# Virtual environments (if you ever create one in this folder)
venv/
env/
.venv/

# OS-specific junk files
.DS_Store          # macOS
Thumbs.db          # Windows

# Streamlit's local cache (safe to regenerate, no need to track)
.streamlit/secrets.toml   # NEVER commit secrets/API keys if you add any later

# Editor/IDE folders
.vscode/
.idea/

# Raw dataset — uncomment the line below if your CSV contains
# data you don't have rights to publish publicly.
# Telco churn dataset (IBM sample data) is freely redistributable,
# so it's safe to commit, but keeping this here as a reminder
# pattern for future projects with private data:
# *.csv
